{{Infobox hospital | name = Princess Christian Maternity Hospital'''Princess Christian Maternity Hospital''' | org/group = | logo = | logo_size = | image = | image_size = 225 | alt = | caption = | coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline, title}} --> | location = [[Freetown]], [[Sierra Leone]] | region = | state = | country = | healthcare = <!-- UK: NHS; AU/CA: Medicare; ELSE free-form text, e.g. Private --> | funding = | type = Maternity | affiliation = | patron = | network = | standards = | emergency = Yes | beds = | speciality = | helipad = No | h1-number = | h1-length-f = | h1-length-m = | h1-surface = <!-- up to h12 --> | founded = <!-- cite in article as well --> | closed = | demolished = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | other_links = | module = }}
'''Princess Christian Maternity Hospital''' is a [[hospital]] in [[Freetown]], [[Sierra Leone]] nicknamed the 'Cottage Hospital'. On May 2006 [[Ahmad Tejan Kabbah]] re-opened the hospital alongside [[Connaught Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Historical Background of Re-Opening Hospitals | publisher = Ministry of Health & Sanitation | year = 2006 | url = http://www.health.sl/hosp_history.htm | accessdate = 2008-04-12}}</ref>
==2014 Ebola epicemic== Princess Christian Maternity hospital came under severe pressure during the [[2014 Ebola virus epidemic in Sierra Leone]]. Scientific studies have shown that pregnant women are amongst the least likely to survive an onset of [[ebola]], most likely because the mother's body lowers its [[immune response]] to prevent it rejecting the baby.<ref name="Lang">{{cite news |first=Joshua |last=Lang |date=29 October 2014 |title=Ebola in the Maternity Ward |newspaper=The New Yorker |url=http://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/ebola-maternity-ward}}</ref> In a previous outbreak in [[Zaire]], 14 out of 15 pregnant women who contracted the disease died.<ref name="Lang"/> With the country's health facilities completely overrun and already unable to cope with the patient numbers, the authorities decided to place pregnant women last in the queue for treatment, and also segregated them from other ebola patients, under the assumption that there was little that could be done to save them.<ref name="Lang"/> Most of the pregnant ebola patients were sent to Princess Christian, but with health resources committed elsewhere, the hospital was severely neglected and conditions were so bad that the [[United Nations]] proposed closing the hospital altogether.<ref name="Lang"/>
