'''May Charlesworth''', known as '''Violet Charlesworth''' (born January 1884) was a British fraudster.<ref name="thomas">{{cite book|last1=Thomas|first1=Harry|title=Harry Thomas' Memory Lane, Volume 1|date=2003|publisher=Gwasg Helygain|isbn=9780952275565|page=32-33|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FZXHihBd-AIC&lpg=PA32&ots=4P2bJp0dck&dq=%22violet%20charlesworth%22&pg=PA32#v=onepage&q=%22violet%20charlesworth%22&f=false|accessdate=2 May 2018|chapter=Rhyl's fraudulent heiress Violet Charlesworth}}</ref>
After obtaining money by misrepresenting herself as an heiress she faked her death in Wales on 2 January 1909. She was found and brought to trial.<!-- Refs available on talk page -->
She and her mother '''Miriam Charlesworth''' were sentenced to three years' penal servitude (reduced from an initial sentence of five years when the judge reconsidered his verdict); their appeal against the sentence was dismissed.<ref name="times24feb">{{cite news|title=The Assizes: Midlands Circuit: The Charlesworth Case: Sentence|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/newspaperRetrieve.do?sort=DateAscend&docLevel=FASCIMILE&prodId=TTDA&tabID=T003&bookId=&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchId=R5&currentPosition=23&qrySerId=Locale%28en%2C%2C%29%3AFQE%3D%28tx%2CNone%2C19%29violet+charlesworth%3AAnd%3ALQE%3D%28da%2CNone%2C12%29%3E+01%2F01%2F1900%3AAnd%3ALQE%3D%28gs%2CNone%2C6%29%22News%22%24&retrieveFormat=MULTIPAGE_DOCUMENT&bucketSubId=&inPS=true&userGroupName=lancs&hilite=y&docPage=article&nav=next&docId=CS68221528&searchTypeName=AdvancedSearchForm&contentSet=LTO|accessdate=2 May 2018|work=The Times|date=24 February 1910|page=4}}</ref><ref name="times26feb">{{cite news|title=The Assizes: Midlands Circuit: Mrs. and Miss Charlesworth: Sentence reduced|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/newspaperRetrieve.do?sort=DateAscend&docLevel=FASCIMILE&prodId=TTDA&tabID=T003&bookId=&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchId=R5&currentPosition=25&qrySerId=Locale%28en%2C%2C%29%3AFQE%3D%28tx%2CNone%2C19%29violet+charlesworth%3AAnd%3ALQE%3D%28da%2CNone%2C12%29%3E+01%2F01%2F1900%3AAnd%3ALQE%3D%28gs%2CNone%2C6%29%22News%22%24&retrieveFormat=MULTIPAGE_DOCUMENT&bucketSubId=&inPS=true&userGroupName=lancs&hilite=y&docPage=article&nav=next&docId=CS67566170&searchTypeName=AdvancedSearchForm&contentSet=LTO|accessdate=2 May 2018|work=The Times|date=26 February 1910|page=4}}</ref><ref name="times19mar">{{cite news|title=Court of Criminal Appeal: Rex v. Charlesworth|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/newspaperRetrieve.do?docType=LTO&contentSet=LTO&sort=DateAscend&docLevel=FASCIMILE&type=multipage&retrieveFormat=MULTIPAGE_DOCUMENT&version=1.0&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&docPage=article&source=gale&contentSet=LTO&callistoContentSet=UDVIN&inPS=true&newScale=0.33&tabID=T003&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=lancs&docId=CS67304051&queryId=&currentPosition=1&sort=DateAscend&searchId=&recNum=CS67304051&searchTypeName=&fromContentPage=articleOnThisPage&articleContentLink=enable&browseByDate=enable|accessdate=2 May 2018|work=The Times|date=19 March 1910|page=4}}</ref>
She was released from prison in February 1912<ref name="wanganui">{{cite news|title=Violet Charlesworth released|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WC19120213.2.21.37|accessdate=2 May 2018|work=Wanganui Times|issue=12849|date=13 February 1912}}</ref> but nothing is known of her later life.
Her story attracted international attention.<ref name=wanganui /><ref name="nyt">{{cite news|title=FIND GIRL SWINDLER; IS ALIVE AND WELL; Violet Charlesworth, Who Said She Was Heiress to Millions, Is at Oban, Scotland. A TELEGRAM GAVE CLUE Sister Who Declared Violet Was Tossed from Motor Over Cliff Goes to Her.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1909/01/18/archives/find-girl-swindler-is-alive-and-well-violet-charlesworth-who-said.html|accessdate=2 May 2018|work=New York Times|date=18 January 1909}}</ref>
