{{Infobox college coach | name = William L. Allen | image = William L. Allen 1900.png | alt = | caption = Allen from the 1900 ''Michiganensian'' | sport = [[American football|Football]] | birth_date = c. 1877 | birth_place = [[Iowa]] | death_date = May 13, 1907 (aged 30) | death_place = [[Las Vegas, New Mexico]] | alma_mater = [[University of Michigan]] | player_years1 = 1897–1898 | player_team1 = [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]] | player_positions = [[Guard (American and Canadian football)|Guard]] | coach_years1 = 1899 | coach_team1 = [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]] (varsity reserves) | coach_years2 = 1900 | coach_team2 = [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington Agricultural]] | coach_years3 = 1902 | coach_team3 = [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington Agricultural]] | overall_record = 6–3–1 | bowl_record = | tournament_record = | championships = | awards = | coaching_records = }} '''William Lindsay Allen''', sometimes identified as '''William Luedyard Allen''', (c. 1877 – May 13, 1907) was an [[American football]] player and coach. He played [[college football]] at the [[University of Michigan]] and was a player on the [[1898 Michigan Wolverines football team]] that won the school's first [[Big Ten Conference|Western Conference]] championship. During the 1900 and 1902 college football seasons, he was the head football coach at Washington Agricultural College and School of Science—now known as [[Washington State University]]—in [[Pullman, Washington]]. He compiled a record of 6–3–1 as the head coach at Washington Agricultural.
==Early years== Allen was born in approximately 1877 and was a resident of [[Sac City, Iowa]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Calendar of the University of Michigan 1899-1900|publisher=University of Michigan|year=1900|page=328|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kec_AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> He was the son of William Allen (born c. 1816 in Virginia) and Sarah Allen (born c. 1847 in Wisconsin). At the time of the 1880 United States Census and the 1885 Iowa Census, the family was living at Sac City.<ref>Census entry for William Allen, Sarah Allen, and children Hattie, Willie and Richmond. Willie was listed as being three years old, born in Iowa. Ancestry.com and The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. 1880 United States Federal Census [database on-line]. Year: 1880; Census Place: Jackson, Sac, Iowa; Roll: 363; Family History Film: 1254363; Page: 177A; Enumeration District: 187; Image: 0034.</ref><ref>Census entry for William Allen, Sarah Allen, and William L. Allen. Ancestry.com. Iowa, State Census Collection, 1836-1925 [database on-line].</ref>
Allen began his education at the [[University of Notre Dame]].<ref name=Ens/> In 1897, he enrolled at the University of Michigan as student in the Department of Laws. As a first-year student in 1897, Allen was the vice president of his class and the captain of the varsity reserve football team. As a second-year student in 1898, he played at the [[Guard (American and Canadian football)|guard]] position for the undefeated [[1898 Michigan Wolverines football team]] that won the school's first [[Big Ten Conference|Western Conference]] championship.<ref name=Ens/><ref>{{cite web|title=1898 Football Team|publisher=Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1898fbt.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1898 Michigan Football Roster|publisher=Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan|url=http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1898&-max=170&-Find}}</ref> He was a starter at guard in Michigan's 21–0 victory over [[Eastern Michigan Eagles football#Normalites era (1891–1928)|Michigan State Normal]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Trying Out Men: U. of M. Coaches Had Twenty-Four in the Normal Game; Three Touchdowns in Fair Shape Marked the First Half; The line Slowed Down in Second, One Score Being Made|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 2, 1898|url=}}</ref> its 29–0 victory over [[Kenyon College]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan 29; Kenyon, 0|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=October 9, 1898|page=7|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/422993791.html?dids=422993791:422993791&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Oct+09%2C+1898&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=Michigan%2C+29%3B+Kenyon%2C+0.&pqatl=google}}</ref> and its 12–5 victory over Illinois,<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Wins An Easy Victory: Illinois Plays the Wolverines Close in the First Half Only|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 13, 1898|page=6|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/423053411.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+13%2C+1898&author=&pub=Chicago+Daily+Tribune+(1872-1922)&edition=&startpage=6&desc=MICHIGAN+WINS+AN+EASY+VICTORY.}}</ref>
As a third-year student, Allen was the coach of the varsity reserves football team.<ref name=Ens>{{cite book|title=Michiganensian|year=1900|page=70|url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/m/moa/aag4364.1900.001/72?q1=allen&view=image&size=175}}</ref> He graduated from Michigan with a Bachelor of Laws degree as part of the Class of 1900.<ref>{{cite web|title=Student Profile William Lindsay Allen|publisher=University of Michigan Law School|url=http://www.law.umich.edu/historyandtraditions/students/Pages/ProfilePage.aspx?SID=6214&Year=1900}}</ref>
==Washington Agricultural== [[File:1900 Washington Agricultural College football team.png|left|thumb|180px|1900 W.A.C. football team, Allen at lower right]] After graduating from Michigan, Allen was hired as the head football coach at Washington Agricultural College (now [[Washington State University]]) in [[Pullman, Washington]]. He led the team to an undefeated record of 4–0–1 in the 1900 college football season.<ref name=Chinook/> In his first four games as the head coach, Allen's team won shut out victories over L.A.A.C. (2–0 on October 13, 1900 at Lewiston), S.A.A.C. (6–0 on October 20, 1900 at Pullman), W.W.A.C. (5–0 on November 10 at Walla Walla), and S.A.A.C. (21–0 on November 24 at Spokane). The season ended with a 5–5 tie in a Thanksgiving Day game with the [[University of Washington]] in Seattle.<ref name=Chinook>{{cite book|title=Chinook|year=1902|page=73|publisher=Washington Agricultural College|url=https://research.wsulibs.wsu.edu:8443/xmlui/handle/2376/2634}}</ref> The 1902 Washington Agricultural yearbook, the ''Chinook'', noted: "The football teams during the season just past have, for the first time in the history of athletics at the W. A. C., had the assistance of a coach. W. L. Allen, a graduate of the University of Michigan, was procured by the Athletic Association to coach the men; he was very successful and has built a strong foundation for our future in football."<ref>{{cite book|title=Chinook|year=1902|pages=68, 70|publisher=Washington Agricultural College|url=}}</ref> He returned to coach the team in 1902 and compiled an overall record of 6–3–1.<ref>[http://cfreference.net/cfr/school.s?id=549 College Football Reference] Washington State University Football Records</ref><ref>[http://sports.miamiherald.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=miami2&page=cfoot/teams/direct628.htm Miami Herald] Washington State University all-time football records</ref>
==Later years== By 1902, Allen had moved to [[Seattle, Washington]].<ref>{{cite book|title=General Catalogue of Officers and Students, 1837-1901|publisher=University of Michigan|year=1902|page=323|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gKwiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> He died in May 1907 at [[Las Vegas, New Mexico]], and was buried at [[Cherokee, Iowa]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Necrology|newspaper=The Michigan Alumnus|date=April 1908|page=30|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PA0rAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
